26 april
iouffrour bouton
bulst
volgens u.l brief van 20 feb: lest heeft iacob de vlieger mij comen
betaelen en hebbe sedert verstaen dat marous de vrent doet is. ick
ben verwondert dat mij heer blanchaert soo lanck dikeert dot betaeling
van de verloopen sonder de quitantie aen u gesonden isser wederop
een iaer verachtere. soo u.l het gelt noch niet hebt ontfangen
soo bidde gaet spreckt hem uyt mijnen naem, ende vraght wat
reden dat ick 3 saeren moet laeten verloopen daer andere ieder iaer
ontfangen ende soo hij geen gelt gelieft te gerven sent aen mij de
quitantie cito wederom sal sien andere middel te vinden tot
betaelingh angesloeten eenen brief aen de procureur volckaert
den 8: hem selven gelieft te beandigen ende versoecke ten eersten
daer over de willen antworden het welck verwacht hebbe blijve.
Brussel Anthoni Rousseau
depuis ma derniere dhier receu les 2 vres du memdae pour la
remise de £ 414 sur godevaert schaep il dit quil payora lundy prochain
a cause que de femme en a ordorne a 2 iours de vre aen obstante quil
soit accepte le 25 meij 1694 de 8 sance, cependant si vous ne
voulez pas que i'attend ce temp la ordonne le protest iaij ioint
les 2 autres petittes p le mesme accepte, puisque mont vre beau
frede soit recevent, ivous me pourrez rendre tout le requise pour
le fond de mille livres que ie vous prie de mettre dans le levec
de ƒ125000 a scavoir cineggent livres sur mon nom et £500:
ser le nom de ma belle soeur onne bouwens a condition que iaurez
avec les lettres des rente copies des actes requises comme au pied de cette
comme ondonne ordinairement entel occasion pour la valeur vous prerck
sur moy quand il vous plaira avue peasse, ou si vous me lcaurez quand
largent doit estre conte pourroit estoe pie ie fournerois partie dicy
pour la lettre de ƒ62½ pistoles le Sr bombardo estant en hollande gra
adiusse a son retour puisque ie suis
28 april 95
londen Richard Southeel
6 posts been come together finde 2 of yours of 22 past & 9 cur
goods must be vere scareie that I have no accompts yett whoever
I hope you shall not disapoint mee, butt gett all cleare readdy for
this convoij for ostend, wheater 2 english man of warr are goeng to
convoij the ammonition ships, & where with I suppose the vessels
that there loaden will depart, & I shall finde my self disapointed
in case non copachs comes with them from you, yett haveinge ordered you to
ship what you shall have readdy for mee, little op much, so must
exspect other letters to know what is past, in the meane time so is my
order to buy, when the opportunitie best shall presents 50 white
benc
flannel yard broads assorted from 14 a 15 to ef must part about
17 a 17 & 4 curious ones of about & a 23 pen & when white cottons
& cheapeck
shall be best to be had, to buy 12 demie p from 20 to 22 pince a goad
to be one pack, & each to be measmed afte particularley with the yeard
& in the invoyce to note, first the yeard, then the good as ithey cost
d0 m kent doth, itt beenge comodions for us, because wee seel by the
yeards, as soon as Isee invoyces & patt from you, shall order more nor=-
threns& spans clothes, doe as best you can, & as for your sell & rather
be stow 6 pence mon then I ordered to have a good cloth then abate
a bad prixe to finde my order, for I can better sell a good cloth of
7 a 8& then abad prise of 6 s, when you shall iudge time to buy
goods in the nord, lett them yo white kersies be bonghe 30 yeards
of standsield, rillyes makinge, or standfield or the like, butt I desire
non courser then standfield, lett 30 thers of be send up to londen
to be shipped for ostend & 40 to be send to hull by the first convoy
for holland, lett also be bought 20 heavie white bayes from 44 to
50 & weight & t0 of 40 8 10 of 5 a 36 , 20 of 30 s & 20 of
18 a 9 6 to be 2 packes, for these orders take your owne time &
gett them when you shall iudge best hopeinge that all marketts
shall be well fulled next month & in June when these hasty buyes
shall have their sto mach full, pray speave not now & then a letter
that I might be informed what passes, wee can not butt wonder
to see the running of eoe if itt doth not falli againe, shall bee
att a los, yett wee must have pattence
